If this were a one-time-only event, I wouldn't review it. There have been two such events this summer, and there's a rumor of a third. So, keep an eye on the New Times' Chow Bella blog. If there's another one, GO!  On 8/8, Nobuo Fukuda (formerly of See Saw), his charming wife Sarah, and a few others (with a high tolerance for heat) commandeered the Welcome Diner and put on quite a show. The a la carte menu included:  - Shishito peppers with olive oil and soy sauce - Watermelon and goat cheese with sun-gold tomato, olive oil, and fresh mint - Panko fried soft shell crab sandwich with green papaya slaw - Pork belly with steamed buns - Marinated short rib with steamed buns - Okonomiyaki (a Japanese pancake, in this instance with pork, octopus, squid & topped with pickled ginger, aonori, shaved bonito, dried shrimp, Japanese mayo, and tonkatsu sauce) - Kakigori (Japanese shaved ice: melon, green tea, coffee, or strawberry)  The evening was a lot of fun, and the menu for any further events is TBD. Highlights included the soft shell crab sandwich (ridiculous) and pork belly steamed buns (amazing). The okonomiyaki was delicious, but beware: it can put a dent in one's appetite and curtail pork belly consumption.   Tips: If you get a seat inside, it's going to be about as hot as it is outside. So, wear shorts and sit outside. Also, it's BYOB. There seems to be an issue with alcohol on the patio, so walk into the building to sip (or be really low-profile).

